A great reference for someone starting out with D3 looking to replace some basic jQuery incantations with D3 ones.  I think this code sample is particularly telling:<p><i>jQuery</i><p><pre><code>    $(&#x27;.foo&#x27;).find(&#x27;.bar&#x27;);
</code></pre>
<i>D3</i><p><pre><code>    d3.selectAll(&#x27;.foo&#x27;).selectAll(&#x27;.bar&#x27;);
</code></pre>
The D3 API consistency is so juicy and delicious.

It would be trivial to convert the callback-based method to a promises one in whichever library you&#x27;re using.  For instance, with bluebird[0]:<p><pre><code>    d3.json = require(&#x27;bluebird&#x27;).promisify(d3.json);
</code></pre>
[0]: <a href="https://github.com/petkaantonov/bluebird" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/petkaantonov/bluebird</a>

Someone&#x27;s been confusing syntax and internal representation again.<p>Simple: parse<p><pre><code>  <foo bar=&quot;zot&quot;>quux</foo>
</code></pre>
as (JSON-like)<p><pre><code>  { 
    &quot;foo&quot;: {
       &quot;bar&quot; : &quot;zot&quot;,
       &quot;&quot; : &quot;quux&quot;
     }
  }
</code></pre>
Problem solved, XML is now logical again.
